          "body": "Samuel summons all Israel to Mizpah (7:5), and what follows is one of the Old Testament's most concentrated portraits of corporate repentance. Three acts accompany their confession: they drew water and poured it out before the Lord (7:6), they fasted, and they said 'We have sinned against the Lord.' The water-pouring ritual is unique — appearing nowhere else in the Torah's prescribed liturgy — and has generated scholarly discussion. Most likely it was a symbolic act of self-emptying, perhaps of life and strength, before Yahweh: 'We pour ourselves out before You.' David uses similar language in Psalm 22:14 ('I am poured out like water') in extremis. Whatever its precise meaning, the gesture was public, irreversible, and vulnerable — the opposite of the strategic self-protection that had kept the idols in their houses for twenty years. The verbal confession ('We have sinned against the Lord,' 7:6) is the community's only direct speech in the chapter, and its brevity is deliberate. They do not explain, qualify, or negotiate. They name the sin and own it. This is the confessional pattern John will later codify: 'If we confess our sins, He is faithful and righteous to forgive' (1 John 1:9). Samuel judging the people at Mizpah (7:6) during the assembly indicates that the covenantal governance of the community is being formally reconstituted — the repentance is not just spiritual but structural."
