          "title": "The Philistine threat and Samuel's intercession — crisis as the proving ground",
          "body": "The Philistines' advance on Mizpah (7:7) is not coincidental — it is the chapter's dramatic hinge. The enemy interprets Israel's assembly as a military mobilization; they are correct that something is being consolidated at Mizpah, but wrong about what kind of power it is. Israel's response to the news of the Philistine advance is revealing: they were afraid (7:7), but they did not scatter or reach for weapons. They begged Samuel, 'Do not cease to cry to the Lord our God for us, that He may save us' (7:8). This is the repentance bearing its first visible fruit — a community that has just confessed its sin and submitted to Samuel's leadership now turns to intercession as its primary weapon. Samuel's response is the chapter's liturgical center: he offers a suckling lamb as a whole burnt offering and 'cried to the Lord for Israel' (7:9). The simultaneity of sacrifice and intercession is crucial — atonement and supplication together, not one without the other. God's answer is dramatic and unambiguous: He 'thundered with a great thunder on that day against the Philistines and confused them, so that they were routed before Israel' (7:10). The thunder is an act of divine warfare echoing Sinai (Exodus 19:16-19), the battle against Sisera (Judges 5:20-21), and the Song of Hannah that opens this very book: 'The Lord will thunder from heaven' (1 Samuel 2:10). Israel did not win this battle; they watched God win it, then pursued the broken enemy afterward (7:11)."
