          "body": "Samuel's erection of the Ebenezer stone (7:12) is one of the Old Testament's most theologically concentrated acts. He takes a single stone, sets it between the battlefield at Mizpah and the outcropping called Shen, and names it: 'Thus far the Lord has helped us.' The name does three things at once. First, it reclaims a cursed name — Ebenezer was the site of Israel's catastrophic defeat in chapter 4 (4:1), where the ark was captured and Eli's sons died. Samuel does not avoid the name; he redeems it. The same ground that witnessed Israel's humiliation now witnesses God's help. Second, the name confesses dependence going backward — 'thus far' surveys all the ground between the defeats of chapters 4-6 and this moment of rescue and attributes every step of survival to God's help, not Israel's resilience. Third, 'thus far' looks forward — there is more road, more battle, more need. The stone is not a victory monument; it is a covenant confession that future help will require the same God who helped here. The practice of named memorial is deeply Hebraic: Jacob's Bethel (Genesis 28:19), Moses' 'the Lord is my banner' (Exodus 17:15), and Joshua's stones from the Jordan (Joshua 4:6-7) all share the logic — name what God has done so the next generation knows where to stand when the next Philistines advance."
