          "body": "The chapter's closing verses (7:13-17) are often read as mere appendix, but they are the theological payoff. The Philistines are subdued — not temporarily humiliated but covenantally restrained: 'The hand of the Lord was against the Philistines all the days of Samuel' (7:13). Territorial restoration follows (7:14): the cities from Ekron to Gath are returned, and there is peace even with the Amorites — a detail that signals broader regional stability, not just military truce. Then Samuel's lifelong judgeship is summarized in terms that are deliberately judicial and pastoral, not militaristic. He goes on circuit annually — Bethel, Gilgal, Mizpah, Ramah — four sites that together span the range of Israel's central covenant history (patriarchal sanctuary, conquest entry-point, battle memorial, Samuel's home). He judges in all these places (7:16) and builds an altar at Ramah (7:17). The altar is the final word. Samuel's governance is grounded not in military might or dynastic succession but in sacrifice — in the same posture of intercession and worship that secured the victory at Mizpah. This portrait of ordered community under faithful covenant leadership is the standard the people will abandon in chapter 8 when they demand a king 'like all the nations' (8:5). The reader of chapters 7-8 feels the tragedy: the very gift they are receiving — a whole-hearted judge whose altar is always burning — is the gift they are about to despise."
