        "excerpt": "All the house of Israel lamented after the Lord. Then Samuel spoke to all the house of Israel, saying, 'If you return to the Lord with all your heart, remove the foreign gods…'",
        "body": "The twenty-year gap between the ark's arrival at Kiriath-jearim and Samuel's call to repentance is the chapter's opening tension. The Hebrew verb translated 'lamented' (nahah) carries the connotation of mournful seeking — a sustained, aching longing for what was lost. Israel knew something was wrong. The ark's displacement from the sanctuary, the collapse of Eli's house, the Philistine dominance — these were felt as covenant disruption. But feeling disruption and responding to it covenantally are two different things. The Baals and Ashtaroth were still in place (as 7:4 makes clear by recording their removal as news). Israel had mastered the art of lamenting God's absence while maintaining the idols that caused it.\n\nSamuel's opening word — 'If you return to the Lord with all your heart' — is the covenant pattern of Deuteronomy 30:2 and 10, the foundational promise that exile and loss are reversible upon whole-hearted return. The Hebrew shuv (return, turn) is the Old Testament's primary word for repentance — it is not an emotion but a directional movement. Samuel is not asking for more sincere lamenting; he is demanding a turn. The specific idols named — Baals (storm and fertility gods of Canaan) and Ashtaroth (the female fertility goddess, consort of Baal) — are not abstractions. They were the agricultural gods the Israelites hedged their bets with, worshipping Yahweh for covenant relationship while keeping the Canaanite deities for the harvest. The syncretism was practical, not philosophical.\n\nThe conditional structure of 7:3 is the hinge on which the whole chapter turns: 'If you return… He will deliver you from the hand of the Philistines.' Samuel does not promise comfort or restored feelings of divine nearness. He promises military deliverance — the most concrete and existentially urgent need on Israel's horizon. This is shrewd pastoral theology: the covenant promise is attached to the most acute pressure in the community's life. You want relief from the Philistines? The path runs through the removal of Baal, not around it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nahah* (lamented, 7:2) connotes the mournful seeking of something lost — closer to 'mourning after' than mere complaint. *Shuv* (return, 7:3) is the standard Hebrew word for repentance — a spatial metaphor, a turning around of direction. *Bad* (alone, 7:3) is emphatic exclusivity: serve Him — only Him — no remainder."
