        "body": "Israel's obedience in verse 4 is immediate and complete: they 'removed the Baals and Ashtaroth and served the Lord alone.' The narrator records no debate, no partial compliance, no delay. The word of the prophet was obeyed. Then Samuel calls a national assembly at Mizpah — gathering all Israel for a covenant event, not merely a regional muster. The assembly at Mizpah echoes the great covenant assemblies of Israel's earlier history: the gathering of all Israel at Shechem under Joshua (Joshua 24), the assembly at Mizpah during the Benjaminite war (Judges 20-21), and the covenant renewal under Moses in Deuteronomy. Samuel is reconstituting the covenant community.\n\nThe three acts of the assembly — water-pouring, fasting, and confession — form a triad of covenantal self-humiliation. The water-pouring (shaphakh, 'to pour out') before the Lord is unparalleled in the Mosaic legislation and has attracted varied interpretations. The most contextually satisfying reading treats it as symbolic self-emptying: pouring out life (water as a life-symbol, 2 Samuel 14:14) before Yahweh, a gesture of total vulnerability. It may also echo the libation offerings of the Mosaic system, applied here without a prescribed occasion, as a spontaneous act of devotion. Fasting underscores the community's renunciation of self-sufficiency. The verbal confession — 'We have sinned against the Lord' — is stripped of all qualification. No explanation, no mitigating circumstances, no comparison to the nations around them. The Hebrew chata (to sin, to miss) is simply owned.\n\nThat Samuel 'judged the sons of Israel at Mizpah' (7:6) during the assembly indicates the repentance event is simultaneously a reconstitution of covenant governance. The community is not merely expressing sentiment; it is submitting to the ordered covenant life that had been abandoned in Eli's era. Judgment here is not punitive but administrative — Samuel is re-establishing the judicial and covenant order that should have been Eli's legacy. Peter Davids's observation about James 5 applies here: communal confession and prayer before duly recognized leadership is the pattern for genuine community restoration, not private sentiment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaphakh* (poured out, 7:6) — the same verb used of blood poured out in Levitical sacrifice (Leviticus 4:7) and of soul-pouring in lament (Psalm 62:8). *Shaphat* (judged, 7:6) — to govern, adjudicate, and maintain covenant order. Samuel exercising *mishpat* (justice, governance) during the very assembly of repentance signals that the two are inseparable: spiritual renewal and ordered community belong together."
